<DOC><DOCNO> AP890426-0192 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-89 2010EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-26 0595</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0612</SECOND><HEAD>Damaging Thunderstorms in Iowa; Record Highs in the Southeast, Midwest</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Flooding forced hundreds of West Virginians out of their homesWednesday, and intense thunderstorms pummeled Iowa with winds up to75 mph and hail as big as golf balls.   High-temperature records were set or tied in 12 cities in theMidwest and Southeast, while up to 8 inches of spring snow fell inthe mountains of the West.   Heavy overnight rains in central West Virginia caused floodsthat forced at least 200 people out of their homes Wednesdaymorning and closed schools in four counties, officials said.   Widely scattered light rain and drizzle fell across sections ofthe state during the day, but most small streams receded to normallevels and evacuees returned to their homes in the afternoon.   Some rivers continued to rise. The Little Kanawaha River wasexpected to rise 3 to 4 feet above flood stage at Creston, W.Va.   Northern Iowa's storms blew a roof off a barn and destroyed ahog barn near Little Rock. Winds gusted to 75 mph and golfball-size hail fell in Spirit Lake and gusts were clocked at 70 mphin West Okoboji. In the Estherville area, dime-size hail andthree-fourths of an inch of rain fell in just 20 minutes.   Showers and thunderstorms also fell in southern Minnesota,western Wyoming and central Montana. Rain showers were scatteredacross eastern Washington state.   Snow fell at higher elevations of northwest Wyoming, southeastIdaho. About 8 inches of snow has fallen at the Alta, Utah, skiarea.   The snow was expected to spread across the Montana Rockies. Awinter storm watch was in effect for Wednesday night and Thursdayin the mountains and foothills of Montana and for Thursday insouth-central Montana.   Record heat that baked the western Plains earlier this weekspread Wednesday to the Mississippi Valley and the southernAtlantic Coast. Temperatures were in the 80s and 90s from thesouthern Plains and Kansas to the middle and lower MississippiValley, the western lower Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley, theGulf Coast states, the southern Atlantic Coast and Florida.   High-temperature records for the date were set in eight citiesand tied in four.   Nashville, Tenn., tied its all-time high temperature for April,set in 1980, with a reading of 90 degrees.   Other records included Lincoln, Neb., where the reading of 94degrees exceeded the old mark set in 1987 by 2 degrees; Topeka,Kan., (93, 92 in 1987); Evansville, Ind. (89, 87 in 1981); Paducah,Ky. (87, 85 in 1986) and Charleston, S.C. (90, 88 in 1984).   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 36degrees at Jackson and Cody, Wyo., to 95 degrees at Medicine Lodge,Kan. The nation's low Wednesday morning was 15 degrees in Truckee,Calif.   Thursday's forecast called for scattered showers andthunderstorms from the Plains to the middle and upper MississippiValley and rain showers in parts of the northern and centralRockies, with snow in higher elevations of the northern Rockies.   High temperatures were predicted in the 40s and 50s from easternportions of the north-central Intermountain region to the northernand central Rockies, much of the northern Plains, northernMinnesota, the northern Great Lakes region and New England; the 80sand low 90s from the central and southern Plains to the middle andlower Mississippi Valley, the Tennessee Valley, the Gulf Coaststates, Florida and the southern Atlantic Coast; the 80s in thedesert Southwest; and generally in the 60s and 70s in the rest ofthe nation.</TEXT></DOC>